{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1958"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80944"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1958"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80944"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the transplant clinic for routine follow-up six months after receiving a kidney transplant. She has no significant medical history apart from end-stage kidney disease secondary to IgA nephropathy. Her medications include tacrolimus, prednisolone, and mycophenolate. She feels well and has had no complications since the transplant. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications inhibits inosine monophosphate dehydrogenase (IMPDH), thereby disrupting purine synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tacrolimus","Prednisolone","Azathioprine","Mycophenolate","Cyclosporine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-transplant immunosuppression typically requires multiple medications targeting different pathways of the immune response. \u003Cstrong\u003EMycophenolate\u003C/strong\u003E works by inhibiting inosine monophosphate dehydrogenase (IMPDH), a key enzyme in purine synthesis. This disrupts nucleotide formation and prevents T-cell proliferation, making it an effective immunosuppressant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETacrolimus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyclosporine\u003C/strong\u003E are calcineurin inhibitors that work by blocking T-cell activation through inhibition of interleukin-2 production. They do not directly affect purine synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzathioprine\u003C/strong\u003E is a purine analogue that also interferes with DNA synthesis, but through a different mechanism than mycophenolate. It is converted to 6-mercaptopurine and then to thioinosinic acid, which inhibits several enzymes in purine synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a glucocorticoid that has broad anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive effects through multiple mechanisms, including inhibition of cytokine production and reduction of inflammatory cell migration. It does not specifically target purine synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these different mechanisms is crucial for managing transplant patients, as each medication targets different aspects of the immune response, providing comprehensive immunosuppression while minimising individual drug toxicities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mycophenolate inhibits inosine monophosphate dehydrogenase (IMPDH), preventing T-cell proliferation by blocking purine synthesis.","Post-transplant immunosuppression typically requires multiple agents targeting different immune pathways.","Understanding the mechanisms of immunosuppressive medications is crucial for managing transplant patients."],"references":["Longo DL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Jameson J, Loscalzo J. eds. Harrison\u0027s Principles of Internal Medicine, 18e. New York, NY: McGraw-Hill; 2012."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1958"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T20:52:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T20:55:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1958"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80944"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data